        "arm_group": [
            {
                "arm_group_label": "Early initiation of dialysis", 
                "arm_group_type": "Experimental", 
                "description": "Start of hemodialysis within a maximum of 12 hours after diagnosis of acute renal failure."
            }, 
            {
                "arm_group_label": "Deferred hemodialysis", 
                "arm_group_type": "Active Comparator", 
                "description": "Start of hemodialysis between 48 and 60 hours after diagnosis of acute renal failure."
            }
        ], 
        "brief_summary": {
            "textblock": "Acute renal failure is one of the most feared complications of septic shock and occurs in\n      51% of patients with these conditions. Mortality at 3 months ranges from 36% to 60%. To\n      date, these exists no consensus regarding the optimal time to initiate hemodialysis.\n      Retrospective and observational studies have suggested that early initiation of hemodialysis\n      could help to improve prognosis in these patients. Therefore, we aim to investigate wether\n      early initiation of hemodialysis (within 12 hours after a diagnosis of acute renal\n      insufficiency at the \"failure\" stage according to the RIFLE Criteria), will reduce 90-day\n      mortality as compared to deferred initiation of hemodialysis (48 to 60 hours after\n      diagnosis), in intensive care unit (ICU) patients with septic shock who develop acute renal\n      failure.\n\n      Secondary objectives include: to compare the impact of the two hemodialysis strategies on\n      28, 180 et 360 day mortality, duration of mechanical ventilation, duration of hemodialysis,\n      duration of ICU stay and duration of overall hospital stay. In addition, quality of life at\n      90 and 360 days will be evaluated using the EQ5D questionnaire. Tolerance of both strategies\n      will be compared in terms of metabolic disorders, arrhythmias, pulmonary oedema by overload,\n      hypotension, hemorrhagic complications, and dependence on dialysis at hospital discharge."
        }, 
        "brief_title": "I.D.E.A.L.-I.C.U. (Initiation of Dialysis EArly Versus Late in Intensive Care Unit)", 
